The state \(\widetilde{10}\) is dominated by the unperturbed state with energy \(E^{(0)} = 10\). ### First-Order Correction The first-order correction \(E^{(1)}\) is the expectation value of the perturbation \(H^{(1)}\) in the unperturbed state \(|10\rangle\). Since \(H^{(1)}\) is diagonal in the unperturbed basis, the expectation value is zero: \[ E^{(1)} = \langle 10 | H^{(1)} | 10 \rangle = 0 \] ### Second-Order Correction The second-order correction \(E^{(2)}\) is calculated using the formula: \[ E^{(2)} = \sum_{n \neq 0} \frac{|\langle n | H^{(1)} | 0 \rangle|^2}{E^{(0)} - E^{(0)}_n} \] where \(|0\rangle\) is the unperturbed state with energy \(E^{(0)} = 0\). The relevant matrix elements of \(H^{(1)}\) are: - \(\langle 0 | H^{(1)} | 10 \rangle = 1\) - \(\langle -10 | H^{(1)} | 10 \rangle = 0\) The denominators are: - For \(n = 0\) (state \(|0\rangle\)): \(E^{(0)} - E^{(0)}_0 = 10 - 0 = 10\) - For \(n = -10\) (state \(|-10\rangle\)): \(E^{(0)} - E^{(0)}_{-10} = 10 - (-10) = 20\) Calculating the contributions: - Contribution from \(|0\rangle\): \(\frac{|1|^2}{10} = \frac{1}{10} = 0.1\) - Contribution from \(|-10\rangle\): \(\frac{|0|^2}{20} = 0\) Summing these contributions: \[ E^{(2)} = 0.1 + 0 = 0.1 \] ### Total Energy The total energy up to second order is: \[ E_{\widetilde{10}} = E^{(0)} + E^{(1)} + E^{(2)} = 10 + 0 + 0.1 = 10.1 \] Thus, the energy \(E_{\widetilde{10}}\) rounded to one decimal place is \(\boxed{10.1}\).
